Title : John Gurney Hoare
Text : {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=March 2016}}
'''John Gurney Hoare''' (7 May 1810 – 16 February 1875) was an English [[cricket]]er with [[Amateur status in first-class cricket|amateur status]], later a banker.

==Biography==
Hoare was born in [[Hampstead]], north London, a son of Samuel Hoare (1783–1847), a partner in Bland, Barnett & Hoare, bankers (which after mergers and name changes was eventually taken over by [[Lloyds Bank]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archiveshub.jisc.ac.uk/search/archives/6af0760a-5074-33c5-93c0-46ac916df598 |title=Bland, Barnett & Hoare records |publisher=[[Jisc]] Archives Collection}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lloydsbankinggroup.com/Our-Group/our-heritage/our-history/lloyds-bank/barnetts-hoares-hanbury--lloyd/ |title=Barnetts, Hoares, Hanbury & Lloyd |publisher=Lloyds Banking Group plc}}</ref>) and his wife [[Louisa Gurney Hoare|Louisa]]. Hoare was the grandson of the [[Quaker]] [[Samuel Hoare Jr|Samuel Hoare]], one of the twelve founding members of the [[Society for the Abolition of the Slave Trade]]. John Hoare was educated privately and at [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], where he graduated as 20th [[Wrangler (University of Cambridge)|Wrangler]].<ref name="acad">{{acad |id=HR827JG |name=Hoare, John Gurney}}</ref> He became a partner in his father's bank and inherited Hill House, Hampstead. A plaque near the site of the house states that "he was the prime mover in the battle to save [[Hampstead Heath]] from development."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londonremembers.com/memorials/john-gurney-hoare |title=John Gurney Hoare |publisher=London Remembers}}</ref>

==Cricket==
While he was at Cambridge Hoare appeared in one [[first-class cricket]] match in 1831, playing for [[Cambridge University Cricket Club|Cambridge University]] as a [[batting (cricket)|batsman]] of unknown [[handedness]]. His name was recorded incorrectly as '''James Gurney Hoare'''. He scored nine [[run (cricket)|runs]] over both [[innings]] with a highest score of 7 [[not out]].<ref name="CA37">{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/37/37007/37007.html |publisher=''CricketArchive'' |title=John Hoare}}</ref>

==Family==
On 18 March 1837 at St Martin's church, [[Dorking]], [[Surrey]], Hoare married Caroline Barclay (1814–1878)<ref>Anglican Parish Registers. Woking, Surrey, England: Surrey History Centre. </ref><ref name="acad"/>, daughter of Charles Barclay (1780–1855) and Anna Maria Kett (1781–1840) of [[Cheapside]], London.

Hoare's eldest son Samuel became [[Sir Samuel Hoare, 1st Baronet]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p19651.htm#i196510 |title=John Gurney Hoare |website=thepeerage.com}}</ref>

Hoare died on 10 March 1875 in the Grand Hotel, [[Biarritz]], France<ref>Principal Probate Registry. Calendar of the Grants of Probate and Letters of Administration made in the Probate Registries of the High Court of Justice in England. London, England © Crown copyright. </ref>, and was buried there.
